        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-09-30T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-09-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="328" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d328">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">501.<gloss target="#t_BC1">BC</gloss>/9–3048</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in India</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Donovan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New Delhi</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-09-30">September 30,
                            1948</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">No. 1133</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">Subject: Editorial in Delhi <hi rend="italic">Statesman</hi>,
                    September 30, regarding Hyderabad.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to refer to New Delhi’s telegram
                    no. 896 of September 30, 1948<note n="1" xml:id="d328fn1">Not printed.</note>
                    and to enclose the full text of the editorial which appeared in the Delhi <hi rend="italic">Statesman</hi> of September 30, 1948 entitled “The UN and
                        Hyderabad”.<note n="1" xml:id="d328fn2">Not printed.</note> The views
                    expressed in this editorial are shared by the Embassy. There is no question but
                    that the Nizam, surrounded by a small minority of Muslim extremists, was a
                    menace to the peace and security of India. The question whether Hyderabad was an
                    independent state can no doubt be argued for hours but the blunt facts are that
                    India could not permit a hostile government to function within its borders.</p>
                <p>The Embassy cannot too strongly emphasize that American interests in India would
                    best be served by considering the Hyderabad question as closed.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Howard Donovan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
